05 — Build Phases (8-Day Sprint)
Phase 0 · Days 1–2 · Scaffold & Infrastructure
Tasks: Init monorepo, plug in Clerk auth, connect Postgres on Railway, set up CI/CD, register domain
End state: Skeleton live at pulse.yourdomain.com — a real URL before a single feature is built
Phase 1 · Days 3–4 · Core Analysis Engine
Tasks: Wire Claude API to Express backend, Redis caching (same text = no duplicate API call), rate limiting middleware, connect the PULSE dashboard frontend to real backend
End state: Real AI sentiment analysis working end-to-end in production
Phase 2 · Day 5 · Batch Processing
Tasks: CSV upload with multer, BullMQ job queue (process rows async), progress bar on frontend via polling, download enriched CSV result
End state: Upload 100 rows, get back a fully sentiment-scored spreadsheet
Phase 3 · Day 6 · Projects & History
Tasks: Postgres tables for projects and analyses, save every analysis per user, projects page with create/name/organize
End state: Full analysis history persisted, organized in projects
Phase 4 · Day 7 · API Keys + Landing Page
Tasks: API key generation stored as hashed values in DB, rate-limited to 10 req/day for free tier, public landing page with embedded live demo
End state: Shareable demo link ready, developers can call the API
Phase 5 · Day 8 · Polish & Launch
Tasks: All Pro gates added with upgrade modals, Coming Soon shells built, mobile responsive pass, README with architecture diagram, custom domain wired
End state: Portfolio-grade product fully live

06 — Database Schema
Tables

users — Synced from Clerk (id, email, name, plan, created_at)
projects — Grouping container (id, user_id, name, description, created_at)
analyses — Core record (id, project_id, user_id, input_text, created_at)
results — AI output (id, analysis_id, score, confidence, emotions JSONB, keywords JSONB, sentences JSONB)
api_keys — Developer access (id, user_id, key_hash, name, calls_today, last_used)
usage_logs — Every API call logged (id, user_id, source, tokens_used, created_at)

Key Design Decisions

results stored as JSONB in Postgres — flexible, queryable, no over-engineering
api_keys stores hashed keys only — raw key shown once at generation, never again
usage_logs enables future billing without schema changes
plan field on users enables gating logic without a separate subscriptions table at MVP


